The CompTIA Data+ certification validates your expertise and opens doors to higher-paying roles in IT and cybersecurity. Whether you are just starting your study journey or doing a final review, this guide breaks down everything you need to know to pass the DA0-001 exam.

## Exam Overview

- **Certification:** CompTIA Data+
- **Exam Code:** DA0-001
- **Vendor:** CompTIA
- **Cost:** $358 USD
- **Duration:** 90 minutes
- **Questions:** Up to 90 questions
- **Passing Score:** 675 out of 900
- **Format:** Multiple choice + Performance-based questions (PBQs)
- **Prerequisites:** None required (18-24 months data analytics experience recommended)

## Domain Breakdown

Understanding the exam domains and their weights is critical for efficient study planning. Focus more time on heavily-weighted domains while ensuring you cover all areas.

### Domain 1: Data Concepts and Environments (15%)

- 1.1 Identify basic concepts of data schemas and dimensions
- 1.2 Compare and contrast different data types
- 1.3 Compare and contrast common data structures and file formats
- 1.4 Explain data integration and collection methods

**Key concepts:** Structured vs Semi-Structured vs Unstructured Data, Data Schemas (Star, Snowflake), Data Warehouses vs Data Lakes, ETL vs ELT Processes, Relational vs Non-Relational Databases, Data Types (Discrete, Continuous, Categorical), Common File Formats (CSV, JSON, XML, Parquet), APIs and Web Scraping

### Domain 2: Data Mining (25%)

- 2.1 Explain data acquisition concepts
- 2.2 Identify common reasons for cleansing and profiling data
- 2.3 Given a scenario, execute data manipulation techniques
- 2.4 Explain common techniques for data manipulation and query optimization

**Key concepts:** Data Cleansing Techniques, Handling Missing Values (Imputation), Data Deduplication, Data Normalization and Standardization, SQL Joins (INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, FULL), SQL Aggregation (GROUP BY, HAVING), Filtering and Sorting, Data Profiling

### Domain 3: Data Analysis (23%)

- 3.1 Given a scenario, apply the appropriate descriptive statistical methods
- 3.2 Explain the purpose of inferential statistical methods
- 3.3 Summarize types of analysis and key analysis techniques
- 3.4 Identify common data analytics tools

**Key concepts:** Measures of Central Tendency (Mean, Median, Mode), Standard Deviation and Variance, Correlation vs Causation, Hypothesis Testing (p-values, Confidence Intervals), Regression Analysis (Linear, Logistic), Time Series Analysis, Trend Analysis, Descriptive vs Predictive vs Prescriptive Analytics

### Domain 4: Visualization (23%)

- 4.1 Given a scenario, translate business requirements to visualization
- 4.2 Given a scenario, use appropriate design components for reports and dashboards
- 4.3 Given a scenario, use appropriate methods for dashboard development
- 4.4 Given a scenario, apply the appropriate type of visualization

**Key concepts:** Chart Types (Bar, Line, Pie, Scatter, Histogram), Heat Maps and Geospatial Visualizations, Dashboard Design Best Practices, KPIs and Scorecards, Interactive vs Static Reports, Data Storytelling, Color Theory for Data Visualization, Accessibility in Visualizations

### Domain 5: Data Governance, Quality, and Controls (14%)

- 5.1 Summarize important data governance concepts
- 5.2 Given a scenario, apply data quality control concepts
- 5.3 Explain master data management concepts
- 5.4 Describe the purpose of data standards and policies

**Key concepts:** Data Governance Frameworks, Data Stewardship and Ownership, Data Quality Dimensions (Accuracy, Completeness, Consistency), Master Data Management (MDM), Data Privacy Regulations (GDPR, CCPA, HIPAA), Data Classification (Public, Internal, Confidential), Data Retention Policies, Access Controls and Security


## Recommended Study Timeline

Plan for approximately **6-10 weeks** of dedicated study. Here is a suggested weekly breakdown:

- **Week 1:** Domain 1: Data Concepts — Data types, Schemas (Star, Snowflake), Warehouses vs Lakes
- **Week 2:** Domain 1: Data Environments — ETL/ELT, File formats, Integration methods, APIs
- **Week 3:** Domain 2: Data Mining — Data acquisition, Cleansing, Profiling, Missing values
- **Week 4:** Domain 2: Data Manipulation — SQL joins, Aggregation, Filtering, Query optimization
- **Week 5:** Domain 3: Descriptive Statistics — Mean, Median, Mode, Standard deviation, Variance
- **Week 6:** Domain 3: Inferential Statistics — Hypothesis testing, Regression, Correlation, p-values
- **Week 7:** Domain 4: Visualization — Chart types, Dashboard design, KPIs, Data storytelling
- **Week 8:** Domain 4: Reports & Dashboards — Interactive reports, Drill-down, Accessibility, Color theory
- **Week 9:** Domain 5: Governance & Quality — GDPR, CCPA, Data quality dimensions, MDM, Retention policies
- **Week 10:** Full Review: Practice tests, SQL exercises, Visualization practice, Exam logistics

## Top Study Tips

1. **Start with the official exam objectives.** Download them from the CompTIA website and use them as your study checklist. Every exam question maps to a specific objective.

2. **Use active recall over passive reading.** Instead of re-reading notes, test yourself with practice questions after each study session. This dramatically improves retention.

3. **Focus on heavily-weighted domains first.** Domains with higher percentages appear more on the exam. Master these before moving to lower-weighted areas.

4. **Build hands-on experience.** Set up a lab environment and practice the skills you are studying. Hands-on experience is especially valuable for performance-based questions.

5. **Take practice exams under real conditions.** Time yourself, eliminate distractions, and simulate the exam environment. Review every wrong answer and understand why it was wrong.

